RENOVO RESOURCE SOLUTIONS â€” COMPREHENSIVE UI/UX AUDIT
EXECUTIVE SUMMARY
Current Brand Perception: Industrial Heritage Meets Service Accessibility
Renovo presents as a trustworthy, operationally focused recycling service provider with established legitimacy (ISRI membership, BBB accreditation, chamber affiliations). However, the digital presence reflects a legacy business model rather than a modern, growth-focused enterprise. The brand feels circa 2010sâ€”stable and transparent, but lacking the sophistication, energy, and strategic persuasion that contemporary B2B and B2C audiences expect.
Critical Insight: The website prioritizes compliance documentation and operational information over compelling narrative and user conversion. This is appropriate for a commodity business, but misses significant opportunities to:

Build emotional connection with the sustainability angle
Streamline the customer journey for both residential suppliers and commercial partners
Position Renovo as an innovator in circular economy solutions, not just a processor

Brand Perception Gap: Trustworthy but dated. Safe but forgettable.

DEEP DIVE: UX ANALYSIS
1. NAVIGATION & INFORMATION ARCHITECTURE
Current State:

Flat, horizontal navigation (7 items: Home, Restricted Materials, Scrap Laws, What We Buy, Method of Payment, Contact Us, Board Members)
Clear hierarchy, but no visual prioritization
No mobile-responsive feedback observed; unclear mobile experience

Friction Points Identified:
IssueImpactSeverityNo clear CTA hierarchy â€” Contact Us buried equally with secondary pagesReduces conversion potential for new suppliers/customersHIGH"Board Members" in main nav â€” Corporate governance info alongside customer-facing functionsConfuses information priority; signals B2B-only audienceMEDIUMRestrictive Materials page is dense legal text â€” No scannable summary or visual breaksCompliance > User ExperienceHIGHNo "Pricing/Rates" visible â€” Critical decision factor for supplier suppliers missingMajor conversion barrierCRITICAL"Method of Payment" as page title is passive â€” Should be "Get Paid" or "Instant Payment Options"Weak value proposition framingMEDIUM
Recommended Navigation Restructure:

Primary CTAs: "Sell Your Scrap" | "What We Buy" | "Rates & Pricing" | "Contact/Drop-Off Hours"
Secondary Info: About | Compliance (consolidated restricted materials + scrap laws)
Tertiary/Footer: Board Members, ISRI membership details

2. INFORMATION FLOW & CLARITY
Strong Points:

Hours prominently displayed in header (operational transparency)
Contact phone numbers immediately visible
Location clearly stated

Weak Points:

Homepage hero lacks purpose statement â€” The video of the facility is nice but doesn't explain why someone should use Renovo vs. competitors
"Come Discover the Renovo Difference" is vague corporate speakâ€”What is the difference? (Later we learn: 7-minute average time, 20-customer capacity, 1.5M lbs/month processingâ€”bury this insight at the top!)
"What We Buy" page forces users to browse dozens of material types â€” No filtering, no "Quick Categories," no "Check Current Prices" feature
No path to estimate value â€” A supplier must visit in person or call; creates friction for first-time sellers

3. ACCESSIBILITY & RESPONSIVE DESIGN
Issues Observed:

High contrast on navigation (tan/olive buttons) works, but body text on black backgrounds (hours section) has WCAG compliance questions
No visible skip-to-content link (though one exists in code)
Italicized text in headers is reduced readability
Form fields on Contact page lack visible labels in some renderings


VISUAL DESIGN AUDIT
1. COLOR PALETTE & BRAND IDENTITY
Current Palette:

Primary: Navy blue (logo, strong brand anchor) âœ“
Secondary: Multi-color swoosh (red, yellow, green, blue) â€” dated early-2000s gradient aesthetic
Accent: Olive/tan navigation bar, lime green contact form background
Supporting: Red text ("WE BUY SCRAP METAL"), black body backgrounds, white text

Assessment:

Logo is the brand's strongest asset â€” bold, memorable, distinct
Color scheme feels fragmented â€” the rainbow swoosh, combined with harsh blacks and lime greens, creates a "busy" rather than "premium" impression
No cohesive color language â€” too many hues competing for attention
Lime green (#CCFF00 range) contact forms are jarring â€” feels more "kids' website" than "professional recycling partner"

Perception Impact: The multicolor swoosh reads as "approachable and community-focused" (appropriate for the brand), but the execution feels amateur. There's no sense of refinement.
2. TYPOGRAPHY
Current Stack:

Headers: Italicized serif (elegant in intent, but affects readability)
Body: Sans-serif (appropriate for web)
Italic placeholder text in form fields (low contrast, accessibility concern)

Issues:

Heading italics create visual fragmentation â€” particularly when combined with the busy logo
"We Buy Scrap Metal" in bold red italic feels more aggressive than inviting
No clear type hierarchy â€” multiple heading weights and styles don't establish visual flow
Form labels in italics hard to parse quickly in a mobile context

3. SPACING & LAYOUT
Current Approach:

White space is minimal on the homepage
Dark background creates visual weight
"What We Buy" uses a 3-column grid layout (solid choice for product showcase)
Contact form is well-centered with breathing room (good)

Issues:

Hero video takes up substantial real estate but doesn't communicate value â€” could be replaced with a dynamic, purpose-driven hero section
Testimonials or social proof absent â€” recycling centers rely on trust; where are the happy customer quotes?
No visible metrics dashboard â€” "1.5M lbs/month," "7-minute average," "20 simultaneous customers" are buried in copy, not highlighted as competitive advantages

4. IMAGERY & VISUAL STORYTELLING
Material showcase (What We Buy page):

Strength: High-quality product photography (aluminum cans, radiators, extrusions look industrial and authentic)
Weakness: Lacks before/after storytellingâ€”where does this scrap metal go? What products are made from it? No circular economy narrative

Homepage video:

Shows the facility, which is good for credibility
But lacks emotional resonanceâ€”no people, no transformation story, no environmental impact message


